      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage, you say? High shrinkage in the electronics warehouse? That sounds like a real problem, like a whole horde of mischievous little goblins sneaking off with the shiny gadgets! You can't just ignore those little pilferers, or your inventory turnover ratio will look like a poorly organized goblin hoard—all jumbled and inefficient.\n\nTo factor this increased shrinkage into your inventory turnover ratio, you essentially need to adjust your *Cost of Goods Sold* (COGS). The standard formula is:\n\n$$\\text{Inventory Turnover Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}$$\n\nWhen shrinkage is high, it means some of your recorded inventory isn't actually there to sell, so your COGS needs to reflect the *actual* cost of goods lost, not just what you billed.\n\nHere’s the trick: You need to calculate your **Adjusted COGS**. Instead of just using the standard COGS, you should add the monetary value of the shrinkage to it. Think of the shrinkage as an extra, unrecorded \"cost\" that the goblins have imposed on your operation.\n\n$$\\text{Adjusted COGS} = \\text{Standard COGS",
